data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.3+ supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — no more boxing or type mismatches at runtime
- Square brackets → parentheses (tuples instead of arrays)

The test method signature is validated against the tuple types at compile time, so adding a test case like `(123, false)` would be a compiler error rather than a runtime failure.
